title: Uploading a dataset creates a duplicate dataset
body:
When you upload a dataset, it makes 2 identical datasets

Steps to reproduce the behavior:
 1. Log in
 2. Upload a dataset
 3. Go to "My datasets"

Expected behavior:
 There will be 2 identical datasets created with the given information

Desktop:
 - OS: Ubuntu
 - Browser: chromium
 - Version: 1.0

title: Some workflows are setup in a way to be unnecessarily difficult or outright impossible to pass, while giving no benefits to the CI/CD workflow

labels.name: misc
labels.description: The issue doesn't fit in any other category

body:
When contributing to the repository, the python lint checker is overtly demanding and is thus being ignored by the developing team; Likewise, the conventional commits check is overtly aggressive and checks all commits in the git log, causing an automatic fail due to commits made before instaurating the workflow.

The python linter should be removed or changed to a less strict one, as it is of no use to the current CI/CD; similarly, the conventional commit checker should be fixed as to only care about a reasonable amount of past commits (so it does not fail due to old commits from before it was first created)

title: Unit test for download in different formats
body:
Add Unit Tests for Download Feature in Different Formats

I want to test that the system correctly handles dataset downloads in various formats through the /dataset/download/<int:file_id>/<string:format> endpoint.

The feature supports the following formats: UVL, Glencoe, DIMACS, SPLOT, ZIP. Testing involves verifying that each format triggers the correct redirection and returns the appropriate HTTP status code (302 for valid formats, 400 for invalid ones).

Manual testing is inefficient, error-prone, and not repeatable. Automated unit tests will ensure the functionality works as expected consistently and reliably.

title: fix(dataset): change name of the token
Selenium tests for Download in different formats
body:
I want to test with Selenium that the system allows me to download in the different formats I have.

I considered performing the tests manually, but this approach is less efficient, more prone to errors, and does not allow for consistent and repeatable testing.

The application uses a dropdown menu to select download formats (e.g., UVL, Glencoe, DIMACS, SPLOT, ZIP). Testing involves verifying the correct format is downloaded upon selection.
